				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aelanna" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(334454); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=334454&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182994" alt="Aelanna" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=334454)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aelanna" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(334454); return false;" >Aelanna</a></span> <span class="odate time_1301411678 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Mar 2011 15:14</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1092827">
									

<p>"Capacitor Bank Zero"? "Warehouse Zero"? I'm going to have to say that many people frown upon that kind of naming, as it's a blatant attempt to inflate the importance of your SCP by trying to imply that it's somehow "the original" or "the secret", much like "Patient Zero".</p>
<p>Aside from that, the article seems to suffer from being a bit long and meanders through several side topics that don't seem to help the basic concept. Do you really need that much technobabble to explain how it infiltrates a house and electrocutes individuals? Does it really need to "hunt" certain individuals, making them paranoid in the process? (Besides, that just borders on "things what make people go crazy".) Do you really need the association with St. Elmo's Fire?</p>
<p>Finally, the Special Containment Procedures section is far too long. It's not a comprehensive explanation of how something is contained, it's a quick and dirty briefing in case something goes horribly wrong and we need to know RIGHT NOW how to make sure something is safely contained. Try to keep it at two paragraphs or less if at all possible.</p>

							</div>

								
					
