					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dstecks" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(424615); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=424615&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182994" alt="DStecks" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=424615)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dstecks" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(424615); return false;" >DStecks</a></span> <span class="odate time_1301418533 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Mar 2011 17:08</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1093058">
									

<p>Regarding "things what make you crazy": I think that sometimes, because we're so conditioned to watch out for this, people assume TWMYC is the situation every time an SCP causes mental problems. As far as I can see, there's two ways SCP-induced crazyness goes:</p>
<p>Type A: Primary Effect Insanity<br />
-A Type A effect is the direct effect of the SCP, for example, SCP-AAA is a deck of cards that makes you depressed. That is exactly its effect, the insanity caused defines why it is an SCP. Generally, Type A insanity is a sign of bad writing.</p>
<p>Type B: Secondary Effect Insanity<br />
-A Type B effect is extrapolated from exposure to the SCP, i.e. the SCP does not <em>make</em> you insane, the knowledge of it does. For example, SCP-BBB is a DVD that shows you how you will die. It doesn't physically make you insane, but that knowledge could be bad for your mental health. Generally, Type B insanity is a sign of, if not good writing, at least not bad writing.</p>
<p>Basically, I think the issue is that whenever people see insanity of any kind in an SCP, they assume that it's Type A.</p>

							</div>

								
