				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/gene-r" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(634139); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=634139&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182994" alt="Gene R" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=634139)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/gene-r" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(634139); return false;" >Gene R</a></span> <span class="odate time_1311267370 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">21 Jul 2011 16:56</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1207080">
									

<p>Joules are energy. &quot;Passing an electric current of one ampere through a resistance of one ohm for one second&quot;, to quote the almighty Wikipedia.<br />
When a charge is stored in a capacitor, there's no current.<br />
Imagine a water tower. When filled with water, it has the potential to create a flow of water. Same goes for a charged capacitor - it has a potential to create an electrical flow.<br />
When you open the valve, water starts flowing and you have a current. The speed at which water flows through the pipe is roughly the equivalent of an ampere. The energy the water flows with is enough to propel the water at a given speed. That's Joules.<br />
Farads, in this case, are the amount of water that can be stored in this tower.</p>

							</div>

								
					
